23/11/2004
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- The leaders of Serbia and Republika Srpska met on Monday (22 November) and urged all war crimes suspects to surrender to the UN tribunal. Presidents Boris Tadic and Dragan Cavic and Prime Ministers Vojislav Kostunica and Dragan Mikerevic agreed at a meeting in Belgrade that this would be the best way to co-operate with The Hague tribunal. On Wednesday, chief UN prosecutor Carla del Ponte will present a report to the UN Security Council on co-operation. 
In other news Monday, SFOR troops searched a house belonging to Milan Mladic, the nephew of Ratko Mladic. Documents and photographs reportedly were seized. Separately, SFOR troops searched an Internet cafe in Zenica, looking for activities that run counter to the Dayton Agreement. (Danas, Nezavisne novine - 23/11/04; AFP, PBS BiH, NTV Hayat, Pincom.info, Fena, Beta, Tanjug - 22/11/04) 
